---
import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
---
<DocsLayout
  title="SSL with mkcert"
  description="Generate locally-trusted TLS certificates for your dev domain using mkcert, served via Caddy."
  section="dev"
>
  <p>
    <code>shuttle dev</code> uses <a href="https://github.com/FiloSottile/mkcert" target="_blank">mkcert</a>
    to generate locally-trusted TLS certificates. This gives you a genuine
    <code>https://</code> URL in development — no browser warnings, no self-signed certificate
    errors — matching your production SSL setup.
  </p>

  <h2>Install mkcert</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-bash"># macOS
brew install mkcert
mkcert -install      # installs the local CA into your system trust store

# Linux (Debian/Ubuntu)
sudo apt install mkcert
mkcert -install

# Windows (using Chocolatey)
choco install mkcert
mkcert -install
</code></pre>
  <p>
    The <code>mkcert -install</code> step adds mkcert's root CA to your OS and browser trust stores.
    You only need to run it once per machine. Certificates generated after this step are
    automatically trusted by Chrome, Firefox, Safari, and your system's TLS stack.
  </p>

  <h2>How Shuttle uses mkcert</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>On <code>shuttle dev up</code>, Shuttle checks for existing certs at <code>.shuttle/certs/cert.pem</code>.</li>
    <li>If absent and mkcert is installed, Shuttle calls <code>mkcert -cert-file cert.pem -key-file key.pem &lt;domain&gt; [extra-domains...]</code> and writes the results to <code>.shuttle/certs/</code>.</li>
    <li>The generated Caddyfile mounts <code>.shuttle/certs/</code> as <code>/certs</code> inside the Caddy container and configures <code>tls /certs/cert.pem /certs/key.pem</code>.</li>
    <li>If mkcert is not installed, Shuttle warns and starts without SSL (plain HTTP only).</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Certificate location</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">.shuttle/
  certs/
    cert.pem      # certificate (trusted by your OS after mkcert -install)
    key.pem       # private key
</code></pre>
  <p>
    Certificates are valid for the domains listed in <code>shuttle.yml</code> under <code>domain:</code>
    (or <code>dev.domain</code> if set). They are regenerated each time <code>shuttle dev up</code>
    is called if the cert file is missing.
  </p>

  <h2>Caddy TLS configuration</h2>
  <p>
    The generated <code>.shuttle/Caddyfile.dev</code> looks like this when SSL is available:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-caddyfile">{`my-app.example.com {
  tls /certs/cert.pem /certs/key.pem
  reverse_proxy web:3000
}

localhost {
  tls /certs/cert.pem /certs/key.pem
  reverse_proxy web:3000
}`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    Caddy uses the provided cert/key files directly — it does not attempt to contact Let's Encrypt
    in development. This means no internet connection is required for SSL in dev.
  </p>

  <h2>Fallback without mkcert</h2>
  <p>
    If mkcert is not installed, Shuttle skips the SSL setup and does not start Caddy. Your app is
    still accessible via the ports exposed directly by the Docker Compose service. You will see a
    warning:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">WARN  mkcert is not installed. Install it for trusted local SSL:
      brew install mkcert  (macOS)
      mkcert -install
      Continuing without SSL...
</code></pre>

  <h2>Node.js: trusting the mkcert CA</h2>
  <p>
    Node.js maintains its own certificate store and does not use the OS trust store by default.
    If your app makes outbound HTTPS requests to <code>localhost</code> or your dev domain in
    development, set <code>NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS</code> to point to mkcert's root CA:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">export NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS="$(mkcert -CAROOT)/rootCA.pem"
</code></pre>
  <p>
    Add this to your shell profile (<code>~/.zshrc</code> or <code>~/.bashrc</code>) or to the
    <code>environment</code> block of your service in <code>docker-compose.dev.yml</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Regenerating certificates</h2>
  <p>
    Delete the cert files and run <code>shuttle dev up</code> to regenerate:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">rm -rf .shuttle/certs/
shuttle dev up
</code></pre>
  <p>
    Certificates are valid for 825 days (mkcert's default). You are unlikely to need to regenerate
    them during the lifetime of a project.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
